[Costa Rica reported no deaths due to malaria from 2010-2019 (WHO World Malaria Report 2020; https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789240015791. For 2016, 2017, 2018, and 2019 Costa Rica reported 4, 12, 61, and 87 indigenous malaria cases of which about 90% were _Plasmodium vivax_. No malaria cases were reported in 2013, 2014, and 2015
(WHO World Malaria Report 2020; https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789240015791). - Mod.EP]

[La Trocha, meaning "the trail" in Spanish, is a dirt roadway (also called Route 1856) on the south bank of the San Juan River in Costa Rica, covering completely the northern border of Heredia province to the west of Boca San Carlos in Alajuela province on the border with Nicaragua (https://ticotimes.net/2015/05/13/costa-ricas-border-road-la-trocha-confounds). Also, see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Route_1856_(Costa_Rica). For a map of this area, see https://www.google.com/maps/place/San+Juan+River/@10.6223601,-84.3615554,9z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x8f0af3c89e6079c3:0xb911b2b7bbe7278a!8m2!3d10.917258!4d-84.3172359. - Mod.ML

